r external interference. In summary, the Conduit of Dimensional Equilibrium is an intricate, multifaceted device that embodies the delicate balance between the chaos of the Rift and the structured power of the Eternum Bastion. Its network of pipes not only stabilizes and channels raw energy but also creates a living connection between the Heartstone and the volatile forces that birthed the Bastion. Would you like to explore further details on how players might interact with this system or how it could integrate into in-game rituals and mechanics? The Umbral Maw While it is not really a room it is still a part of the bastion so it will be listed here. There is no escape from the Maw. Not through time. Not through will. Not through death. Deep within the swirling chaos of the Rift, where reality itself fractures and reforms in an unending cycle, lies the Umbral Mawâ€”a prison unlike any other. Unlike mortal dungeons bound by stone and steel, the Maw is a conceptual prison, existing in a state of paradox between dimensions. It is both a place and a living force, a construct of Valtharixâ€™s will designed to hold the most dangerous, rebellious, or simply unfortunate souls who have drawn his ire. The Mawâ€™s Appearance and Structure The Mawâ€™s Outer Form The Umbral Maw is not visible to the untrained eyeâ€”to most, it does not even exist unless Valtharix wills them to see it. However, those with the gift (or curse) of perception describe it as a massive, churning vortex of blackened energy, resembling a colossal wound in reality. It writhes, hungering, its edges flickering between the material and immaterial like a never-ending cosmic storm. When Valtharix calls upon the Maw to take a prisoner, its form shifts, extending inky tendrils into the physical world, pulling the victim inward in an agonizing process that feels like being dragged through the very concept of oblivion itself. The Inner Prison Within the Maw, the true torment begins. The prison does not consist of mere cellsâ€”it is a labyrinth of torment designed to wear down the will of its captives. Shifting Corridors of Madness: The very architecture of the prison refuses to remain constant. A prisoner who walks forward finds themselves right where they started. Doors lead to nowhere or, worse, to places they have already beenâ€”but subtly different in ways that instill deep unease. Timeless Confinement: Time inside the Maw does not flow as it should. Some captives experience centuries within minutes, while others find that years have passed in a single breath. The confusion erodes their sanity, making escape impossible. Endless Echoes: The walls whisper with voicesâ€”sometimes their own, sometimes the voices of long-dead prisoners. At times, the whispers manifest as full-blown hallucinations, tricking the captives into reliving their worst moments. Reflections of Regret: The prisoner is sometimes faced with versions of themselvesâ€”broken, corrupted, or in alternate futures where they had made different choices. These apparitions do not speak; they merely watch, judging. Flesh-Bound Chains: The chains that bind captives here are not made of metal but of the very essence of the Bastion itself. They shift, burrowing into the soul rather than the body, ensuring that even if oneâ€™s physical form is destroyed, their spirit remains trapped. The Mawâ€™s Methods of Torment Valtharixâ€™s prison does not merely holdâ€”it breaks. The Maw ensures that even the strongest will is eventually ground into dust. The Hunger of the Rift: Captives slowly lose pieces of themselves to the Riftâ€™s insatiable hunger. At first, it might be memoriesâ€”small details, a name, a face they cannot quite recall. Then, their sense of self erodes. Eventually, they forget who they are entirely, becoming hollow echoes of their former selves. Prisoners of Perception: Those who resist physical confinement are instead trapped in illusory worlds, endless loops of despair that trick them into believing they ha